collation.p:
A composite manuscript comprised of two unequally sized Parts, the first and larger Part perhaps originally produced as codicological units, with a second Part consisting of a single quire now bound at the end of the volume. The numbering of the quires and the interpretation of their structure that is presented here differs from that in R.M. Thomson's descriptive catalogue.
Quire 18-1 (ff. i-vii) ;
Quires 2-712 (ff. 1-72)
Quire 88-1 (ff. 73-79: 8th leaf excised) ;
Quire 912-1 +1 (ff. 80-91; the leaf originally between the leaves now designated as f. 83v and 84r cancelled, f. 85 inserted)
Quire 1010-3 (ff. 92-98; 8th-10th leaves missing, stubs visible)
Quire 11one (ff. 99; 1st-9th leaves missing and/or excised, stubs visible, 10th leaf remains) ;
Quire 1212 (ff. 100-111)
Quire 136-1 (ff. 112-116: 6th leaf missing)
Quire 144 (ff. 117-120) |
Quire 158 (ff. 121-127 + 128 (right pastedown) ;

Quires of mostly 12 leaves. It is possible that this Part of the manuscript consists of consecutive codicological units (ff. iv-vii; 1-79; 80-99; 100-120), made by several scribes copying their texts siumultaneously rather than sequentially as there are blank columns and leaves at ff. vii verso, 79v, 99v, rather than the more typical copying-practice, where the subsequent text continues on the next line or column after the previous text concludes. In addition, the textual and decorative mise-en-page of ff. iv-120 is similar, but not absolutely identical, and appears to be the work of several contemporary scribes who worked mostly in quire-units but who occasionally reappeared for short stints throughout the volume. The first seven leaves in the volume, ff. i recto - vii verso are treated here as originating from the same source manuscript as ff. 1-120, which differs from the codicological assessments of the volume made by M. R. James and R. Thompson who treat the first quire (ff. i-vii) as a separate codicological Part. The first three leaves (ff. i-iii) are written in an entirely different style to the rest of the volume with a more informal mise-en-page and none of the decorative features present elsewhere in the volume, but are nevertheless part of the same gathering as ff. iv-vii. The text on ff. iv-vii is decorated in a similar style to the text on ff. 1-120, and the scribe who added rubrication instructions to the lower margins of ff. v recto - vii recto appears to be the same scribe as the scribe who was responsible for the same task on ff. 83r-85v. It is possible that the first three leaves of the volume were originally blank protective endleaves for a volume whose 'main' texts started at what is now f. iv recto, but then, as is so common with medieval manuscripts, those blank endleaves were repurposed for the storage of additional text(s). The arrangement of the quires in this Part is as follows:
Quire 18-1 (1st leaf missing; ff. i-vii) ;
Quires 2-712 (ff. 1-72)
Quire 88-1 (8th leaf excised; ff. 73-79) ;
Quire 912-1 +1 (the leaf originally between the leaves now designated as f. 83v and 84r cancelled, f. 85 inserted; ff. 80-91)
Quire 1010-3 (8th-10th leaves cancelled or excised, stubs visible; ff. 92-98)
Quire 1110-9 (1st-9th leaves cancelled or excised, stubs visible, 10th leaf remains; f. 99);
Quire 1212 (ff. 100-111)
Quire 136-1 (6th leaf missing; ff. 112-116)
Quire 144 (ff. 117-120)
